---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Cadence Fitness · Case Study">
  <section>
    <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/case-studies">Case Studies</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span aria-current="page">Cadence Fitness</span>
    </nav>
    <h1 class="hero-title">
      Workout logging that tracks <span
        style="whitespace:no-wrap; display:inline-block"
        >the full picture<span class="flourish-period">.</span></span
      >
    </h1>
    <ul class="meta-list meta-list--casestudy meta-list--pills">
      <li>Self-initiated</li>
      <li>2026</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="hero-wrapper">
      <section class="hero-lead">
        <p>
          <strong>
            A strength training app that captures the context behind each set —
            equipment, variations, rest, and training methods — without slowing
            down logging.
          </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          This project allowed me to develop my use of AI-augmented prototyping
          and development as I worked to solve a real personal pain point.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            >The app is currently enrolled in the Android store closed test
            programme.</em
          >
        </p>
      </section>
      <section class="card card--role card--compact">
        <h2>Role</h2>
        <ul class="role-list">
          <li>Research</li>
          <li>Design</li>
          <li>Content</li>
          <li>Development</li>
          <li>
            Testing <br /><em class="small">(moderated + unmoderated)</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>
    <ul class="tools-list">
      <li>
        <img class="tools-list__icon" src="/images/figma.png" alt="Figma" />
      </li>
      <li>
        <img class="tools-list__icon" src="/images/miro.png" alt="Miro" />
      </li>
      <li>
        <img class="tools-list__icon" src="/images/vscode.png" alt="VS Code" />
      </li>
      <li>
        <img class="tools-list__icon" src="/images/react.png" alt="React" />
      </li>
      <li>
        <img class="tools-list__icon" src="/images/codex.png" alt="Codex" />
      </li>
      <li>
        <img class="tools-list__icon" src="/images/trello.png" alt="Trello" />
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card card-split card-split--2-3 content-block">
    <div>
      <h2>Problem</h2>
      <p>
        Regular gym-goers want to track progress consistently, but variations in
        machine setup and personal settings — even when performing the same
        exercise — make like-for-like comparison unreliable.
      </p><p>
        While the market is saturated with gym trackers and fitness loggers,
        many are expensive and bury basic exercise logging inside bloated,
        non-contextual feature sets. This makes it harder, not easier, to
        understand real progress.
      </p>
      <h3>Validation</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Input from personal trainers and regular gym users.</li>
        <li>
          A short survey shared within fitness-focused social communities.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div>
      <img src="/case-studies/cadence/exercises.png" alt="Exercise" />
      <p class="caption">
        Equipment calibration and settings can significantly impact exercise
        work rate across sessions. <br /><strong>Image: ChatGPT</strong>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Project goals</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Flexible & efficient logging</li>
      <li>Like-for-like, contextual comparison</li>
      <li>In-the-moment progress indicators</li>
      <li>Focused - no fluff</li>
      <li>Offline first</li>
      <li>Cost effective</li>
      <li>Immediate value</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
  <section class="card-split">
    <section class="card">
      <h2>Process</h2>

      <p>A simple process of prototype, refine, test, and iterate.</p>
      <p>
        High-level process flows were defined in Miro, then prototyped and
        refined in Figma.
      </p>

      <p>
        Because the product is offline-first, all data lives on the device. This
        enabled rapid development of an installable proof of concept and
        immediate testing in real workouts with myself and close friends.
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section class="card card--transparent">
    <!-- <h2>Assets</h2> -->
    <h3>Initial concept development</h3>
    <section class="full-bleed">
      <img
        class="full-width-image"
        src="/images/cadence/flowchart.png"
        alt="Flowchart"
      />
    </section>

    figma prototypes VS code protypes figma UI VS code UI In gym test Current UI
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Reflection</h2>
    <p>
      Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Donec vel leo in
      nisi vehicula fermentum. Suspendisse potenti. Phasellus et magna at risus
      bibendum interdum.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
